const faqs = [
  {
    q: "Is BS EN 1176 a legal requirement in the UK?",
    a: "BS EN 1176 is a standard, not a statute. There is no UK law that names BS EN 1176 as mandatory. However, UK operators of play equipment have a legal duty of care under the Health and Safety at Work Act 1974 and the Occupiers' Liability Acts 1957 and 1984. Following BS EN 1176 is the established industry method of demonstrating that duty has been met. In practice, failing to inspect and maintain equipment in line with the standard is treated as evidence of negligence if an injury occurs.",
  },
  {
    q: "How often must playground inspections be carried out?",
    a: "BS EN 1176-7 sets out three inspection regimes with different frequencies. Routine visual inspections are typically done daily or weekly by operator staff. Operational inspections are typically done every one to three months. Annual main inspections must be carried out at least every 12 months and should be completed by a competent person — in the UK, usually an RPII-certified inspector.",
  },
  {
    q: "Who is qualified to carry out a BS EN 1176 annual inspection?",
    a: "The standard requires an independent competent person. In UK practice, this means an inspector certified by the Register of Play Inspectors International (RPII) — either a Post-Installation Inspector (for new or refurbished sites) or an Annual Inspector (for ongoing annual main inspections). Operational and routine inspections do not require RPII certification, but the person carrying them out must be suitably trained and competent.",
  },
  {
    q: "What is the difference between BS EN 1176 and BS EN 1177?",
    a: "BS EN 1176 covers the play equipment itself — structure, dimensions, hazard prevention, inspection, and maintenance. BS EN 1177 is a separate but closely related standard covering impact-attenuating surfacing beneath equipment. The two standards are used together: BS EN 1176 specifies when surfacing is required (based on critical fall height), and BS EN 1177 specifies how that surfacing must perform under impact testing.",
  },
  {
    q: "Does BS EN 1176 apply to domestic playgrounds at private homes?",
